{{BacknetPost|author=[[User:Orfie2|Orfie2]]|message=

<big>'''Why Level 164 of the Backrooms Is Not a Pineapple: A Formal Rebuttal'''</big>

It has come to my attention that a peculiar and persistent misconception has arisen within the more eccentric corners of the Backrooms theorist community—namely, that Level 164, known as “Structures in the Dark,” is, in fact, a pineapple. I rise today, figuratively and literally (I am standing while typing), to dispel this fruity falsehood and to declare with confidence and a mild headache: Level 164 is not, has never been, and will never be a pineapple.

Let us begin with the basics. A pineapple is a tropical fruit. It has a spiky, green top, a yellowish interior, and tastes like sunshine got lost in a citrus forest. Level 164, meanwhile, is a vast, mostly flat plane of darkened terrain, crisscrossed by crumbling roads, streetlights that flicker without electricity, and mysterious structures scattered like forgotten LEGO pieces. One of these things can be diced and put on pizza to ruin it. The other contains an abandoned Wendy’s that screams at midnight.

Pineapples are found in warm, sunny environments, often accompanied by coconuts, beaches, and suspiciously photogenic parrots. Level 164, by contrast, exists in eternal twilight, with a sky that looks like someone forgot to plug in the stars. The only birdlike thing present is a malformed weathervane that spins violently whenever someone whispers the word "suburban." If you brought a pineapple to Level 164, it would likely wither, cry, and then get hit by a rogue shopping cart.

Now, some have argued—poor, deluded souls—that Level 164 is metaphorically a pineapple, citing its “prickly atmosphere,” “core of mystery,” and the way one always feels slightly sticky while exploring it. To these folks I say: metaphors are not excuses for incorrect taxonomy. By that logic, my Aunt Carol is a train station because she “feels like a place people pass through emotionally.” That may be true, but it’s not science.

Furthermore, pineapples do not contain roads, warehouses, billboards that only say “WHY?”, or libraries where the books whisper secrets about your childhood regrets. I have sliced many pineapples in my day. None of them contained a sketchy convenience store where the clerk stares at you even when he’s blinking. If your pineapple does contain these things, please contact local authorities immediately and do not eat it.

Lastly, consider the implications of calling Level 164 a pineapple. This would require us to reevaluate the entire Backrooms classification system. Is Level 0 a banana peel? Is Level 7 a soggy zucchini with abandonment issues? Is Level Fun a sentient cupcake that screams when frosted? Madness lies down this path. Delicious, absurd madness.

In conclusion, while Level 164 may be dark, mysterious, occasionally juicy (depending on the weather), and confusing to those who try to understand it, it is not a pineapple. It is a grim, surreal stretch of land haunted by the echoes of purpose and powerlines that lead nowhere. It is a liminal horror tapestry of concrete and shadow. A pineapple is a fruit. Level 164 is a vibe.

Thank you for coming to my TED talk. Please take a complimentary kiwi on your way out.}}
