<big>'''Why Level 164 IS a pineapple: The long unwanted sequel to a necropost'''</big>



The word 'Pineapple' originates from a Proto-West-Germanic word that originally meant Pinecone. A pinecone generally means the fruit of a Conifer. Conifer comes from Latin 'Conus', from Greek 'Konos', and ultimately from Proto-Indo-European '*ḱeh₃-', meaning to sharpen. Thus, tracing etymological roots, Pineapple can mean anything sharp. As multiple sharp objects exist within the level, including the floors, grass, wood, and buildings, the vast majority, if not all, of Level 164 can be considered a Pineapple. The term pine, from Proto-Indo-European '*peyh₂-', also means 'To be swollen', or 'to be filled'. Even if there was nothing to be found in Level 164, there must be a space (the level), and an observer (you) to confirm that there is nothing. As we can observe, Level 164 is full of flora and fauna in the form of entities, as well as objects replicating manmade ones. Thus, once again, I have proven that Level 164 is a pineapple.}}
{{BacknetPost|author=[[User:Orfie2|Orfie2]]|message=My Esteemed Opponent,

Your argument contains several fatal flaws of logic, linguistics, metaphysics, botany, and possibly geometry. Allow me the honor of gently dismantling it like a Jenga tower made of damp linguistics textbooks.

First, while “pineapple” did indeed derive from a word meaning pinecone, and pinecones are indeed the seed-bearing structures of conifers, your claim that this makes “pineapple” equal to “anything sharp” commits the classic scholarly sin of etymological inflation—the belief that a word’s ancestral meaning controls its modern usage.Under that logic, “nightmare” would still refer specifically to a demon that sits on your chest at night, and “cereal” would require religious worship.

A troubling breakfast, to be sure.

Furthermore, “sharp” is a broad category. Many things are sharp: knives, heartbreak, cheddar cheese. By your definition, all of these would qualify as pineapples. So would the tip of a pencil, a well-delivered insult, and the corners of IKEA furniture.This is taxonomically unmanageable and, frankly, dangerous.

You also invoke the PIE root meaning “to be swollen,” claiming it describes Level 164 because it contains space, objects, flora, fauna, and “you.”By this logic, every known physical location is a pineapple: your room, Nebraska, the Moon, the empty space inside a Pringle can after you’ve eaten them in a moment of emotional weakness--all pineapples.

This would collapse the entire concept of fruit classification in one linguistic swing. Botanists everywhere would scream.

Additionally, Level 164 contains buildings, roads, lampposts, and in at least one known instance, a garage full of mysterious beige buckets. Unless the modern botanical community has silently reclassified suburban infrastructure as tropical fruit (which, to be fair, would be extremely funny), these features do not meet any criteria for pineappleness in either modern or historical senses.

Finally--and this is essential--pineapples are biological, while Level 164 is ontologically architectural. If you bite a pineapple, juice comes out. If you bite a Level 164 building, you will require dental assistance. No amount of etymological acrobatics transforms concrete into produce.

Therefore, while your argument is bold, creative, and slightly worrying, it collapses under the weight of its own linguistic ambition.

Level 164 is not a pineapple. It is, at best, pineapple-adjacent in spirit.

Respectfully submitted, A Concerned Anti-Fruit Formalist.}}
